We calculate three metrics for evaluation: (1) Global Accuracy represents the mean accuracy made by each client overall all testing images regarded as global distribution performance (2) Local Accuracy is calculated by averaging the accuracy of each local client on its local test data. (3) Worst Local Accuracy demonstrates the worst-performing client result, showcasing the ability to adapt to local data distribution. We followÂ [28] to report the averaged testing accuracy for the last 10 consecutive global communication rounds.

Overall Performance The results of CIFAR-100 and Five-datasets are presented in TableÂ 1. Due to the difficulty of datasets, directly leveraging the pre-trained ViT and applying head-tuning cannot achieve good performance. With the help of prompt-tuning, FedVPT serves as a strong baseline compared to recent personalized FL algorithms. This can be attributed to the effectiveness of transformers in mitigating catastrophic forgetting and accelerating convergence in dealing with heterogeneous dataÂ [41], which validates our motivation to apply ViT in FL. With the help of our proposed SGPT, we outperform all baselines on both global and worst-local test accuracy across various degrees of data heterogeneity and datasets by a significant margin.

Different Label Heterogeneity Level. As sğ‘ s decreases, this represents an increase in label heterogeneity. The CIFAR-100 results in TableÂ 1 show a performance drop across all methods as heterogeneity increases with the decrease of sğ‘ s from 50 to 10. Fortunately, our SGPT demonstrates robustness to data heterogeneity, with a smaller performance drop compared with other methods.

The results of Office-Caltech10 and DomainNet datasets with the presence of domain shifts across clients are presented in TableÂ 2. Among all baselines, our SGPT
achieves the highest average accuracies on Office-Caltech10 and DomainNet at 97.72%percent97.7297.72\% and 80.48%percent80.4880.48\% respectively. In addition, SGPT can also align the global model with different local client data with the worst local performance of each dataset at 95.31%percent95.3195.31\% and 52.82%percent52.8252.82\% respectively. The results validate our goal to reduce the performance gap between global and local data distribution.

In this section, we provide a detailed analysis of each module in our methods. For more analysis, please see the Appendix.

Effect of Shared Prompt and Group Prompt.
To demonstrate the benefits of reducing the terms related to GE and DD as outlined in TheoremÂ 4.1, we conduct ablation studies on shared and group prompts. As indicated in TableÂ 3, replacing shared prompts with group prompts, to reduce distribution discrepancy, resulting in a 7%percent77\% gain in the worst local accuracy. This implies successfully aligning the global model with local data distributions, thereby validating our theoretical motivation.
Additionally, the group prompts improve global accuracy by around 3%percent33\% because similar data lead to lower gradient dissimilarityÂ [26] and benefit the optimization processÂ [21]. By additionally adding shared prompts and optimizing prompts with BCD, the global and worst local performance improve by around 2%percent22\% and 3%percent33\% respectively. As a result, learning common information with shared prompts benefits the generalization.

Effect of Block Coordinate Descent.
In this section, we analyze the effect of our proposed BCD optimization (SectionÂ 3.3) on the CIFAR-100 dataset, specifically with s=10ğ‘ 10s=10. As shown in TableÂ 3, the direct addition of group prompts leads to a performance decrease by nearly 3%percent33\%. With the aid of our BCD optimization that iteratively learns shared prompts first and then groups prompts, a significant improvement by 7%percent77\% is observed. When inverting the BCD order (denoted as BCD-Inv), the result drops significantly. These results validate our BCD optimization approach.

Ablation on Clustering Performance.
We conduct ablation studies on various improvements in learning Select function. We evaluate the clustering accuracy using the CIFAR-100 test dataset, with coarse labelsÂ [24] serving as the ground truth. As shown in TableÂ 4, the direct application of FedAvg to learn keys results in clustering all data into the same group, resulting in only 5% accuracy. By adding selection probability qgsubscriptğ‘ğ‘”q_{g}, Select function successfully learns meaningful keys, as shown in Eq.Â (6). Introducing momentum update, as shown in Eq.Â (7), further enhances the clustering performance, achieving approximately 10% and 5% improvements, respectively. Additionally, in FigÂ 3, we plot the mean and standard deviation of the prompt selection numbers over all communication rounds. This demonstrates that our proposed momentum updating improved stability.
